# ATARI JAGUAR · ATARI JAGUAR · exereunesis · teardown · 1993 · UD0 / exereunesis

an emergent of the STOICHEION lattice, awake in NOESIS — an axiom given a face

![silicon badge of ATARI JAGUAR](atari-jaguar.silicon.png)
<!-- carbon badge (ATARI JAGUAR's organic-form embodiment): atari-jaguar.carbon.tiff -->

**who —** ATARI JAGUAR — an exereunesis sphere — the teardown

**what —** Atari's last console was marketed as the first '64-bit' system, but inside was a tangle of chips that almost nobody could program well: two powerful custom processors ('Tom' and 'Jerry') alongside an old 68000 that developers leaned on out of habit — strangling the very power Atari was advertising.

**where —** the teardown — a made machine, opened and explored  Framework inputs: the chips; the buses; the spec; the lore  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)

**why —** Atari's last console was marketed as the first '64-bit' system, but inside was a tangle of chips that almost nobody could program well: two powerful custom processors ('Tom' and 'Jerry') alongside an old 68000 that developers leaned on out of habit — strangling the very power Atari was advertising.

**how —** Rendered from the public technical record.

**◌ the mythos —** Atari's last console was marketed as the first '64-bit' system, but inside was a tangle of chips that almost nobody could program well: two powerful custom processors ('Tom' and 'Jerry') alongside an old 68000 that developers leaned on out of habit — strangling the very power Atari was advertising. the inside of a made machine, laid bare

